### Create Basic and Filtered Views - PostgreSQL

Source: https://github.com/drizzle-team/drizzle-orm-docs/blob/main/src/content/docs/views.mdx

Declares a user table and creates two views in PostgreSQL: a basic view selecting all users and a filtered view for customers only. Uses pgView from drizzle-orm/pg-core to define views with query builders.

```typescript
import { pgTable, pgView, serial, text, timestamp } from "drizzle-orm/pg-core";

export const user = pgTable("user", {
  id: serial(),
  name: text(),
  email: text(),
  password: text(),
  role: text().$type<"admin" | "customer">(),
  createdAt: timestamp("created_at"),
  updatedAt: timestamp("updated_at"),
});

export const userView = pgView("user_view").as((qb) => qb.select().from(user));
export const customersView = pgView("customers_view").as((qb) => qb.select().from(user).where(eq(user.role, "customer")));
```

```sql
CREATE VIEW "user_view" AS SELECT * FROM "user";
CREATE VIEW "customers_view" AS SELECT * FROM "user" WHERE "role" = 'customer';
```

--------------------------------

### Declare Drizzle ORM Views with Raw SQL and Explicit Schema (TypeScript)

Source: https://github.com/drizzle-team/drizzle-orm-docs/blob/main/src/content/docs/views.mdx

Illustrates how to define both regular and materialized views in Drizzle ORM using the `sql` operator. This method is essential when the Drizzle query builder does not support the required SQL syntax, allowing direct SQL injection while explicitly defining the view's column schema.

```typescript
// regular view
const newYorkers = pgView('new_yorkers', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name').notNull(),
  cityId: integer('city_id').notNull(),
}).as(sql`select * from ${users} where ${eq(users.cityId, 1)}`);

// materialized view
const newYorkers = pgMaterializedView('new_yorkers', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name').notNull(),
  cityId: integer('city_id').notNull(),
}).as(sql`select * from ${users} where ${eq(users.cityId, 1)}`);
```

--------------------------------

### Create PostgreSQL Regular and Materialized Views

Source: https://github.com/drizzle-team/drizzle-orm-docs/blob/main/src/content/docs/views.mdx

Creates both regular and materialized PostgreSQL views using pgView and pgMaterializedView. Demonstrates configuration options like checkOption, securityBarrier, securityInvoker, fillfactor, and tablespace settings. Uses common table expressions (CTEs) with subqueries to filter users by age and city.

```typescript
// regular view
const newYorkers = pgView('new_yorkers')
  .with({
    checkOption: 'cascaded',
    securityBarrier: true,
    securityInvoker: true,
  })
  .as((qb) => {
    const sq = qb
      .$with('sq')
      .as(
        qb.select({ userId: users.id, cityId: cities.id })
          .from(users)
          .leftJoin(cities, eq(cities.id, users.homeCity))
          .where(sql`${users.age1} > 18`),
      );
    return qb.with(sq).select().from(sq).where(sql`${users.homeCity} = 1`);
  });

// materialized view
const newYorkers2 = pgMaterializedView('new_yorkers')
  .using('btree')
  .with({
    fillfactor: 90,
    toast_tuple_target: 0.5,
    autovacuum_enabled: true,
    ...
  })
  .tablespace('custom_tablespace')
  .withNoData()
  .as((qb) => {
    const sq = qb
      .$with('sq')
      .as(
        qb.select({ userId: users.id, cityId: cities.id })
          .from(users)
          .leftJoin(cities, eq(cities.id, users.homeCity))
          .where(sql`${users.age1} > 18`),
      );
    return qb.with(sq).select().from(sq).where(sql`${users.homeCity} = 1`);
  });
```

--------------------------------

### Define PostgreSQL View with Row-Level Security in Drizzle ORM (TypeScript)

Source: https://github.com/drizzle-team/drizzle-orm-docs/blob/main/src/content/docs/rls.mdx

This code snippet demonstrates how to define a PostgreSQL view (`pgView`) in Drizzle ORM and enable Row-Level Security (RLS) on it. By setting `securityInvoker: true` in the `.with()` options, the view will enforce RLS policies based on the invoker's permissions, ensuring data access is restricted appropriately.

```ts
...

export const roomsUsersProfiles = pgView("rooms_users_profiles")
  .with({
    securityInvoker: true,
  })
  .as((qb) =>
    qb
      .select({
        ...getColumns(roomsUsers),
        email: profiles.email,
      })
      .from(roomsUsers)
      .innerJoin(profiles, eq(roomsUsers.userId, profiles.id))
  );
```

### Views > Schema Inference

Source: https://github.com/drizzle-team/drizzle-orm-docs/blob/main/src/content/docs/views.mdx

When views are created using either inlined or standalone query builders, Drizzle ORM automatically infers the view columns schema from the query definition. However, when you use raw SQL operators to define your view, you must explicitly declare the view columns schema yourself. This automatic inference provides type safety and reduces boilerplate when using the query builder approaches.

